    part: "E",
    priority: "⭐⭐⭐⭐",
    summary: { 
      en: "Chapter 12 examines share capital fundamentals. Members become such by: agreement + register entry (entry essential). Share = transferable property carrying rights, measured by nominal value (face value). Types of capital: issued/allotted (shares in hands of members), called-up (amount company required shareholders to pay), paid-up (amount actually paid), loan capital (borrowed money—NOT share capital, must be repaid). Share types: ordinary (residual interest after prior claims, highest risk/reward), preference (prior right to fixed dividend before ordinary, cumulative unless stated non-cumulative, usually no vote), redeemable (bought back by company per terms), treasury (company's own shares held, max 10%, can re-sell). Class rights (dividends, capital, voting) variation requires 75% class consent; 15% minority can apply to court to cancel. Allotment: directors need authority (articles or ordinary resolution); pre-emption rights (offer to existing first unless disapplied). Rights issue (new shares for cash—members pay) vs. bonus issue (from reserves—free, fully paid). Share premium (excess over nominal) goes to share premium account (treated as capital). CANNOT issue at discount (below nominal)—criminal offense, shares treated as fully paid despite discount.",
      bg: "Глава 12 разглежда основи на акционерния капитал." 
    },
